      "culturalSignificance": "Xenia was fundamental to ancient Greek society, enabling trade, diplomacy, and cultural exchange in a world without hotels or police. The concept created networks of alliance spanning the Greek world and beyond. Violation of xenia was among the gravest offenses. The principle influenced later Western concepts of hospitality, the sanctity of host-guest relationships, and international law regarding ambassadors and guests. Modern ethics of hospitality, refugee protection, and guest rights trace to xenia. The concept remains relevant to discussions of immigration, hospitality, and treatment of strangers."
